<paragraph blockId="4.[188,1399,1912,2009]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Our study indicates the existence of four independent species within the complex under consideration: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sakai" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[190,286,1948,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutko">
<emphasis box="[190,286,1948,1974]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. lutko</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Higgins" authorityYear="1940" baseAuthorityName="Higgins" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[300,446,1948,1973]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mimetica">
<emphasis box="[300,446,1948,1973]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. mimetica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kolesnichenko &amp; Kotlobay, 2022" authorityName="Kolesnichenko &amp; Kotlobay" authorityYear="2022" box="[460,628,1948,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shahvarica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[460,628,1948,1974]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. shahvarica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[635,728,1948,1974]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Coutsis &amp; van Oorschot" authorityYear="2014" box="[787,933,1948,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="timandra">
<emphasis box="[787,933,1948,1974]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. timandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species is well differentiated into two subspecies that are isolated both geographically and ecologically.
</paragraph>
